<DOC><DOCNO> AP880308-0016 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0059EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p BC-TexasAt-A-Glance     03-08 0345</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Texas At-A-Glance,370</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are the methods for pickingdelegates from Texas to attend the 1988 Democratic and Republicannational conventions this summer.</TEXT><HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: Bruce Babbitt, Michael Dukakis, RichardGephardt, Albert Gore, Gary Hart, Jesse Jackson, Paul Simon   Pledged delegates: 183   Super delegates: 14   Total: 197   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Friday, June 17 and Saturday, June 18   Texas has a peculiar two-track system for picking its pledgeddelegates to the Democratic National Convention.   Allocation among presidential candidates of the state's 119pledged delegates from congressional districts will be inproportion to the results of the March 8 primary.   However, also on March 8, the state party begins a three-stepsystem of caucuses and conventions that will govern allocation ofthe state's remaining 64 pledged national convention delegates.   The precinct caucuses begin at 7:15 p.m. on March 8 and onlythose who voted in the primary are eligible to participate.Allocation of the 64 pledged delegates at-large will be inproportion to presidential preference expressed at sign-in bydelegates to the state convention on June 18.</TEXT><HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: George Bush, Bob Dole, Jack Kemp, PatRobertson, Pete du Pont, Alexander Haig   Delegates: 111   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Wednesday, June 15   Results of the Republican primary in Texas will governallocation of the state's national convention delegates amongpresidential candidates.   A candidate receiving more than 50 percent of a vote in acongressional district is entitled to all three of that district'sdelegates. If no candidate receives a majority in a district, theone receiving the most votes will get two delegates and thesecond-place finisher will get one.   All 30 of the delegates at large will be awarded to thecandidate receiving at least 50 percent of the vote statewide. Ifno candidate gains a majority, the delegates will be distributedproportionally among the candidates receiving at least 20 percentof the vote.</TEXT></DOC>